2500|$|The Persian slave Piruz Nahavandi (also {{known as}} Abu Lulu) brought a {{complaint}} to Umar {{about the high}} <b>tax</b> <b>charged</b> by his master Mughirah. Umar wrote to Mughirah and inquired about the tax; Mughirah's reply was satisfactory, but Umar held that the <b>tax</b> <b>charged</b> to Abu Lulu was reasonable, owing to his daily income. Umar then {{is reported to have}} asked Abu Lulu: [...] "I heard that you make windmills; make one for me as well." [...] In a sullen mood, Piruz said, [...] "Verily I will make such a mill for you, that the whole world would remember it".|$|R
