40|$|In this paper, {{we examine}} Ricardian {{equivalence}} of debt and tax finance {{in a world}} in which taxes are not lump-sum but are levied on risky labor income. First, we show that the marginal propensity to consume out of a tax cut, coupled with a <b>future</b> income <b>tax</b> increase, is positive under reasonable assumptions regarding preferences toward risk. Second, we document that the degree of income uncertainty facing the typical individual orfamily is large. Third, we show that, for plausible utility function parameters and distributions of future income, the MPC out of a tax cut is quantitatively large. Indeed, the MPC out of a tax cut, coupled with a <b>future</b> income <b>tax</b> increase, can be closer to the Keynesian value that ignores the <b>future</b> <b>tax</b> liabilities than to the Ricardian value that treats <b>future</b> <b>taxes</b> as if they were lump-sum. ...|$|R
